\begin_layout Standard
In order to divide a general Fourier series in symmetry adapted terms we
 should apply one projector for each irreductible representation (irrep)
 of the group to the raw series :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathcal{P}}{}^{\Gamma}=\frac{d_{\Gamma}}{g}\overset{g}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\mathcal{X}^{\Gamma}(A_{i})\cdot\hat{\mathcal{A}}{}_{i}\label{eq:projector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{P}}{}^{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the projector related to the irrep 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the group order (number of operations), 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}(A_{i})$
\end_inset

 is the character of operation 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the irrep 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{A}}{}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an operator which depends on the function that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{P}}{}^{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 is applied to.
 In our case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathcal{A}}{}_{i}f(\boldsymbol{x})=f(A_{i}^{-1}\boldsymbol{x})\label{eq:operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The form of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 varies respect to the kind of object that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 represents.
 We can assume, for the extent of this document, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 is an element of a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}=(V,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

